{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ea599803-d262-4e1e-809f-6378232f1487","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After a SDK update, this is what you want; it pulls the workload versions that are compatible with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the *already-resolved* workload versions. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but does **not** upgrade anything. If your workloads are simply outdated for the new SDK, repair won't help.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, check that `maui` (or `maui-android`, `maui-ios`, etc.) is listed in `dotnet workload list`. If missing, install it explicitly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b5282bbf-7d22-4109-a27e-2fa828890006","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":281,"requestId":"D444:7818E:1CFCBD9:208C5D5:6A07C0FF"},"id":"21c1da88-fbbf-4ecd-8637-9cc0219fcfac","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:57:43.449Z","parentId":"1eced227-4c42-49f7-ac48-efa51518105b"}
